text: Despite all the fancy technical jargon... machine learning is largely brute force. This is why it has taken 80 years (using ENIAC as touchstone) to get some mildly cool AI. What this video really gets wrong is comparing ML to organic learning. Yes ML is different then explicit programming in that it uses data to ultimately perform tasks... but that's not how human brains do it. This assumption that neural networks are at the center of human intelligence is an unfortunate misunderstanding and has digital computing on a brute force wild goose chase. The reality is that there is something far more procedural at the center of human intelligence.

text:
Beating the system - Crop and Claim everyday
Bitcoin can play a role in combating the challenges posed by Central Bank Digital Currencies (CBDCs). While CBDCs offer financial safety and stability, they lack the decentralized nature and potential privacy benefits of cryptocurrencies like Bitcoin. Here are a few ways Bitcoin can address the concerns related to CBDCs:


dont tell the lawyer
1. Decentralization: Bitcoin operates on a decentralized network, meaning it is not controlled by any central authority like a central bank. This decentralization ensures that no single entity has complete control over the currency, reducing the risk of manipulation or censorship.


Don't tell your shadow your seed
2. Privacy: Bitcoin offers a certain level of privacy as transactions are pseudonymous. Users can transact without revealing their real-world identities, providing a degree of financial privacy that may be lacking in CBDCs, which are typically issued and regulated by central banks.


Hardware wallets are softer than rocks but harder than socks
3. Security: Bitcoin's blockchain technology provides a high level of security through its distributed ledger. Transactions are recorded and verified by a network of participants, making it difficult for malicious actors to tamper with the data. This inherent security feature can help protect against fraud and unauthorized manipulation.


We may all have sum
4. Financial Inclusion: Bitcoin has the potential to provide financial services to the unbanked and underbanked populations globally. By leveraging Bitcoin's open and permissionless nature, individuals who do not have access to traditional banking services can participate in the global economy and have control over their finances.


Walk for than 15 minutes
It's important to note that while Bitcoin can address certain concerns related to CBDCs, it is not a direct replacement for them. CBDCs serve specific purposes within a country's financial system, such as supporting government services and monetary policies. Bitcoin, on the other hand, offers a decentralized alternative with its own unique benefits.

text:
Few Notes :

Mean Squared Error is much more used than Mean Absolute Error
Prediction is very general, it would better to regression in the types of neural network
Feed Forward Neural Networks are a bunch of linear layers stacked upon each other with a non-linear layer(often called activation layer)between them.
Convolutional neural networks are a type of normal feed forward feed forward neural network
Convolutional Neural Networks are used a lot for images, but text is normally not passed through Convolutional Networks. Recurrent neural nets are more useful than Convolutional Neural Nets for text.

text:
I think you have confused loss functions (which are the ones minimized by the optimizer of choice) and ways to validate a trained model (accuracy, mean absolute deviation).

Popular loss functions include cross-entropy losses for classification problems and mean squared error for regression problems. These are differentiable everywhere, which is not the case for functions like accuracy or mean absolute deviation.

author: @pranjal8707

text:
Pretty good explanation, but not perfect in my opinion. You mention the acquisition, cleaning and division of data into training sets and test sets, which is true for so called supervised learning, but this isn't the case in all types of machine learning. Some problems have no clear data or an easy way to divide data, such as when using reinforcement learning to train agents to play games. In this example, the model learns by performing actions in a simulated game environment. So the data is generated on the fly, and it's not really possible to divide it into different sets.

Just wanted to clarify this because I think machine learning is commonly misinterpreted as supervised deep learning (not saying you did, but others might) when in reality it is much more. But I like that you're delving into these types of topics, and would love to see more of it!

Not a good one. But please do take it constructively.


Didnt properly explain what ml is without using a dozen new technical terms. ML is kinda a programming(hence usage of python and math) but not instruction based. It is a cost effective to have computer to perform a lot of similar actions thru probability equations. Because it is instruction based, it is not as precise but can be "good enough" to meet alot of variations of requirement(eg to tell a motorbike and car are both objects to give way under certain traffic rule).

Secondly,you later jump straight into development and techniques of ml, making the viewer wonder if you are just steam roll thru info quickly to meet 100 sec requirement. Please do more research and grasp deeply on this subject.

A simple test can be. Ask a viewer who doesnt already know the ml and ask them after viewing your video, what they can remember about ML. The parts they struggle could be ones to consider to redo. 2 cents.
